{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"223c2219-245a-4f34-b595-7fced6761493","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me give you direct guidance instead.\n\nHere are the main tools for analyzing `.dmp` files from .NET apps:\n\n### `dotnet-dump analyze`\n```bash\n# Install the tool\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Open the dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n\n# Useful commands inside the analyzer:\n> clrstack          # managed call stack\n> pe                # print last exception\n> dumpheap -stat    # heap summary\n> eestack           # all thread stacks\n```\n\n### `lldb` (Linux/macOS)\n```bash\n# With SOS plugin\ndotnet-sos install\nlldb --core your-file.dmp\n(lldb) clrstack\n(lldb) pe\n```\n\n### WinDbg (Windows)\nOpen the dump in WinDbg, load SOS (`.loadby sos coreclr`), then use `!clrstack`, `!pe`, `!dumpheap`, etc.\n\n**Recommended first steps:**\n1. Run `pe` (print exception) to see if an unhandled exception caused the crash\n2. Run `clrstack` to see the managed call stack at the time of the crash\n3. Run `eestack` to inspect all threads\n\nWould you like help running any of these tools on your dump file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fd08535a-e194-44d6-a45f-e9ce2afa401d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\". So that skill is not appropriate here.\n\nI should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing their dump file.","outputTokens":452,"requestId":"2053:37135:7A3014:8D9AD3:69F01359"},"id":"0efb0da9-65b3-4be2-949d-2748bf4e1bbb","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:54:45.973Z","parentId":"7a0c78f1-f275-4eff-b48b-4f0d48d91a